b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["Let’s be real: Steam’s dominance isn’t about features—it’s about inertia. Players tolerate its janky UI, its ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://store.steampowered.com/news/","children":"‘soon™’ updates"}],", and its refusal to let you actually ",["$","em",null,{"children":"own"}]," your games across platforms because, well, ",["$","em",null,{"children":"where else are you gonna go?"}]," Epic’s store is a coupon dispenser, GOG is niche, and Amazon’s Luna is… existing, apparently. So when Google waltzes in with ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.notebookcheck.net/Google-is-expanding-Play-Games-on-PC-with-more-titles-native-PC-game-support-broader-hardware-compatibility-and-tighter-continuity-between-Android-and-Windows-PCs.772477.0.html","children":"‘Buy Once, Play Anywhere’"}],"—a promise Steam has ",["$","em",null,{"children":"technically"}]," made since 2011 but only delivers in fits and starts—it’s worth a raised eyebrow.\nThe pitch is simple: Buy a game on Android, play it on your Windows PC, no re-purchases, no cloud-streaming jank. Google’s expanding Play Games on PC with more titles, native PC support (not just emulation), and broader hardware compatibility. On paper, it’s the cross-platform dream players have been begging for—especially mobile gamers who’ve watched their libraries rot on phones while PC ports get ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.pcgamer.com/genshin-impact-is-getting-a-pc-port-but-its-not-the-one-you-want/","children":"abandoned or monetized into oblivion"}],". But here’s the catch: Google’s track record with gaming is ",["$","em",null,{"children":"checkered"}],". Remember ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.theverge.com/2023/1/18/23560862/google-stadia-shutdown-refunds-faq","children":"Stadia"}],"? Yeah, us too.\nThe ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"COMMUNITY PULSE"}]," is already a Rorschach test. Over on ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.reddit.com/r/AndroidGaming/","children":"r/AndroidGaming"}],", the top comment under the announcement is a meme of a guy setting himself on fire labeled ‘Google entering the gaming market.’ Meanwhile, ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://steamcommunity.com/app/221410/discussions/","children":"Steam forum threads"}]," about Play Games’ expansion are a mix of ‘finally, competition!’ and ‘lol, good luck with that.’ The pattern? Players ",["$","em",null,{"children":"want"}]," this to work—they’re exhausted by fragmented libraries and Steam’s monopolistic vibes—but trust is a four-letter word when Google’s involved.\nSo what’s the ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"PATCH TRANSLATOR"}]," take? For mobile gamers, this could mean ",["$","em",null,{"children":"actual"}]," PC versions of titles like ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Genshin Impact"}]," or ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Honkai: Star Rail"}]," without the emulation hassle. For PC purists, it’s a chance to dip into Android exclusives without a phone. But the devil’s in the details: Will saves sync flawlessly? Will multiplayer work cross-platform? And—crucially—will Google stick around long enough to iterate?"]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/googles-steam-gambit-buy-once-play-anywhere-actual/subtitle.jpg","alt":"The one feature Steam still won’t give you (and why players are side-eyeing Google)","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],"$L13"]}],"\n","$L14"]}]
