14:["$","p",null,{"children":["The ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"PLAYER EXPECTATION"}]," vs. reality gap here is ",["$","em",null,{"children":"wide"}],". Players don’t just want cross-platform play—they want ",["$","em",null,{"children":"cross-platform progress"}],". Imagine grinding for months in ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Diablo Immortal"}]," on your phone, only to hit PC and find your inventory wiped because ‘oops, different versions.’ Google’s promising ‘tighter continuity,’ but until we see it in action with, say, ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Call of Duty: Mobile"}]," or ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Apex Legends Mobile"}],", it’s vaporware with a press release.\nThen there’s the ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"BACKLASH RADAR"}],". Three friction points: 1. ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"The ‘Google Graveyard’ Effect"}],": Stadia’s ghost haunts this announcement. Players remember ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.engadget.com/2019-03-19-google-stadia-price-release-date-games.html","children":"promises of ‘the future of gaming’"}]," turning into refund emails. Will Play Games suffer the same fate if engagement lags? 2. ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"The ‘But What About Mods?’ Problem"}],": PC gamers live and die by mods. Steam Workshop is a mess, but it’s ",["$","em",null,{"children":"their"}]," mess. Google’s ecosystem has zero modding culture—can it even compete? 3. ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"The ‘Why Not Just Use an Emulator?’ Pushback"}],": For years, players have used ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.bluestacks.com/","children":"BlueStacks"}]," or ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.ldplayer.net/","children":"LDPlayer"}]," to run Android games on PC. Why switch to Google’s official (and likely more restricted) version?\nThe wild card? ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"Hardware compatibility"}],". Google’s touting support for ‘low-end PCs,’ which could rope in laptops and budget rigs that Steam often ignores. If Play Games runs ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Monument Valley"}]," smoothly on a $300 Chromebook, that’s a flex Valve can’t match. But if it’s just another storefront with a gimmick, players will bounce faster than a ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Fortnite"}]," default skin from a sweat lobby.\nEarly signals suggest Google’s playing the long game—partnering with devs like ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.krafton.com/","children":["Krafton (",["$","em",null,{"children":"PUBG"}],")"]}]," and ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://wildrift.leagueoflegends.com/","children":["Riot (",["$","em",null,{"children":"League of Legends: Wild Rift"}],")"]}]," to ensure big names are on board. But as any ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Destiny 2"}]," player will tell you, ‘partnerships’ don’t mean squat if the execution is botched. The real test starts when the first AAA Android-to-PC port drops—and we see whether it’s a ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Hades"}],"-level triumph or a ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Diablo Immortal"}],"-level dumpster fire."]}]
